Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 3: Are there any missing values in the data? If yes, treat them using an appropriate method¶

In [30]:
# Check for missing values in the dataset
missing_values = foodhub_data.isnull().sum()

# Display the number of missing values for each column
print("Missing values in each column:")
print(missing_values)

# Replace 'Not given' entries in the 'rating' column with NaN to handle them as missing values
foodhub_data['rating'].replace("Not given", pd.NA, inplace=True)

# Re-check for missing values after replacing 'Not given'
missing_values_after_replacement = foodhub_data.isnull().sum()

# Print the missing values again to see the changes
print("\nMissing values after treating 'Not given' in 'rating' column:")
print(missing_values_after_replacement)

# Convert the 'rating' column to a numeric type, handling any non-numeric entries
foodhub_data['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(foodhub_data['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Calculate the median rating
median_rating = foodhub_data['rating'].median()

# Fill missing values with the median rating
foodhub_data['rating'].fillna(median_rating, inplace=True)

# Convert the filled ratings to integer type since ratings are integers
foodhub_data['rating'] = foodhub_data['rating'].astype(int)

# Final check to ensure there are no more missing values
final_missing_values = foodhub_data.isnull().sum()
print("\nFinal missing values after treatment:")
print(final_missing_values)

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer¶

In [41]:
# Ensure the 'rating' column is numeric
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Filter the restaurants based on the given criteria
restaurant_ratings = df.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].agg(['count', 'mean'])

# Filter restaurants with more than 50 ratings and an average rating greater than 4
eligible_restaurants = restaurant_ratings[(restaurant_ratings['count'] > 50) & (restaurant_ratings['mean'] > 4)]

# Print the eligible restaurants
print("Restaurants eligible for the promotional offer:")
print(eligible_restaurants)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders¶

In [42]:
# Calculate the company's revenue based on the order cost
def calculate_revenue(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

# Apply the revenue calculation to each order
foodhub_data['revenue'] = foodhub_data['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_revenue)

# Calculate the total net revenue generated by the company
total_revenue = foodhub_data['revenue'].sum()

# Print the total net revenue
print(f"Total net revenue generated by the company: ${total_revenue:.2f}")

Total net revenue generated by the company: $6166.30

Observations:¶

  • The total net revenue generated by the company across all orders is $6166.30.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations)¶

Conclusions:¶

  1. Popular Restaurants and Cuisines:

    • Shake Shack and The Meatball Shop are the most frequently ordered from restaurants, indicating their strong customer preference.
    • American cuisine is the most popular, especially on weekends, which highlights a consistent demand for this type of food.

  2. Customer Behavior:

    • A significant portion of orders (approximately 29.24%) costs more than $20, indicating that customers are willing to spend more on certain orders.
    • 10.54% of orders take more than 60 minutes to deliver, which could impact customer satisfaction.

  3. Ratings and Restaurant Performance:

    • Restaurants with a high number of orders generally have better ratings, but there are outliers where popular restaurants could improve their service to achieve higher ratings.
    • There are a few restaurants eligible for promotional offers based on their ratings and order volume, suggesting that these restaurants are consistently delivering high-quality service.

  4. Delivery Time Insights:

    • The mean delivery time is shorter on weekends (22.47 minutes) compared to weekdays (28.34 minutes), possibly due to fewer orders or less traffic congestion on weekends.

Recommendations for Business Improvement:¶

  1. Enhance Delivery Efficiency:

    • Focus on reducing delivery times during weekdays, where delivery times are longer compared to weekends. This could involve optimizing delivery routes, increasing the number of delivery personnel during peak hours, or implementing incentives for faster deliveries.

  2. Targeted Promotions for High-Rated Restaurants:

    • Offer more visibility and promotions to restaurants with ratings above 4 and more than 50 orders. These restaurants have proven their quality and reliability, and promoting them can drive more business.

  3. Focus on High-Spending Customers:

    • Since a significant percentage of orders exceed $20, consider offering loyalty programs or discounts to customers who frequently place higher-value orders. This could incentivize repeat purchases and boost customer retention.

  4. Improve Service for Outlier Cases:

    • Investigate the reasons behind the 10.54% of orders that take more than 60 minutes to deliver. Identifying patterns (e.g., specific times of day, certain areas) can help address issues and improve overall service quality.

  5. Leverage Popular Cuisines:

    • With American cuisine being the most popular, consider expanding partnerships with high-quality American restaurants or introducing new American cuisine options in underserved areas. Promotions around this cuisine type could also be effective in driving orders.

  6. Use Feedback for Continuous Improvement:

    • Encourage more customers to leave ratings by simplifying the feedback process or offering small incentives for providing feedback. This can help gather more data to identify areas for improvement and make more informed decisions.

By implementing these recommendations, the company can enhance customer satisfaction, optimize delivery operations, and boost overall revenue.
